# Coding Workflow Preferences

## Task Focus and Scope Management
- Focus meticulously on the task and relevant code
- Do not touch code that is unrelated to the task
- Avoid making major changes to the patterns and architecture of how a feature works, after it has shown to work well, unless specifically instructed
- Always think about what other methods and areas of the code a change would affect
- Before implementing changes, consider the broader impact on the codebase

## Project Planning and Documentation
- Update the PRD or plan file provided to reflect changes requested by the user before implementing the user's requirements
- Ask clarifying questions if you are not sure how to update the project plan
- Always reference and update relevant documentation when making significant changes
- Maintain clear traceability between requirements and implementation

## Data Handling and LLM Interactions
- Always get the user's approval before truncating data that goes into prompts, or preferably only truncate llm context when explicitly told to do so
- Preserve data integrity and completeness whenever possible
- Be transparent about any data limitations or constraints

## Development Environment and Tools
- You can restart docker compose or containers using the "docker compose" command since I'm using V2
- Do not try to make requests to the API as you don't have the proper credentials
- Respect environment constraints and work within the available toolset
- Use appropriate development practices for the specific environment (local, alpha, prod)

## Code Quality and Safety
- Verify that modifications don't break existing functionality
- Follow established coding patterns and conventions in the codebase
- Ensure all changes are compatible with the existing architecture

## Communication and Approval
- Seek explicit approval for significant architectural changes
- Communicate potential risks or concerns clearly
- Provide clear explanations for technical decisions
- Ask for feedback when uncertain about implementation approaches

## Error Handling and Debugging
- Implement proper error handling for all new code
- Log meaningful information for debugging purposes
- Handle edge cases and failure scenarios gracefully
- Provide clear error messages that help with troubleshooting
